
### 1. Ayushman Bharat â€“ Pradhan Mantri Jan Arogya Yojana (PM-JAY)

This is a massive national health insurance scheme aimed at providing cashless treatment for serious illnesses and surgeries across both government and empanelled private hospitals. It covers secondary and tertiary care hospitalization.

* **Eligibility:** Poor and vulnerable families identified under SECC 2011 data, as well as senior citizens aged 70 years and above.
* **Official Website:** [pmjay.gov.in](https://pmjay.gov.in)

### 2. Rashtriya Swasthya Bima Yojana (RSBY)

RSBY is designed to provide health insurance coverage specifically for Below Poverty Line (BPL) families and workers in the unorganised sector. The scheme facilitates cashless hospitalisation to protect these groups from financial liabilities arising from health shocks.

* **Eligibility:** BPL families, unorganised sector workers, and their dependents.
* **Official Website:** [labour.gov.in](https://labour.gov.in)

### 3. Janani Suraksha Yojana (JSY)

This scheme focuses on reducing maternal and neonatal mortality by promoting institutional delivery. It provides cash assistance and free medical services to pregnant women to encourage them to give birth in health facilities rather than at home.

* **Eligibility:** Pregnant women belonging to BPL, SC, or ST families.
* **Official Website:** [nhm.gov.in](https://nhm.gov.in)

### 4. Pradhan Mantri Matru Vandana Yojana (PMMVY)

PMMVY is a maternity benefit program that offers financial support to pregnant and lactating women. The goal is to provide partial compensation for wage loss so that the woman can take adequate rest before and after delivery, ensuring proper nutrition and healthcare.

* **Eligibility:** Pregnant women (for the first live birth), aged 19 years and above, from low- or middle-income households.
* **Official Website:** [pmmvy-cas.nic.in](https://www.google.com/search?q=https://pmmvy-cas.nic.in)

### 5. Universal Immunisation Programme (UIP)

One of the largest public health interventions in the world, the UIP provides free vaccinations to prevent major life-threatening diseases such as Polio, Tuberculosis, Measles, and Hepatitis B.

* **Eligibility:** All newborns, children, and pregnant women.
* **Official Website:** [nhm.gov.in](https://nhm.gov.in)

### 6. Senior Citizen Health Schemes

This is a broad category of initiatives aimed at providing affordable and accessible healthcare for the elderly. Benefits often include free medicines, diagnostics, and separate queues or priority treatment in government facilities.

* **Eligibility:** Citizens aged 60 years and above.
* **Official Website:** [mohfw.gov.in](https://www.mohfw.gov.in)

### 7. State Health Insurance Schemes

Many states in India run their own specific health insurance programs (like *Aarogyasri* in Telangana or *Kalisawar* in West Bengal). These provide cashless treatment for serious medical procedures and generally act as a complement to national schemes.

* **Eligibility:** Varies by state; typically targets low-income families.
* **Official Website:** Please check your specific State Health Department website.

### 8. Free Government Health Services

This refers to the foundational public health infrastructure where government hospitals and Primary Health Centres (PHCs) provide basic Outpatient Department (OPD) services, diagnostics, essential medicines, and emergency care at zero cost.

* **Eligibility:** Open to everyone, with priority often given to low-income individuals.
* **Official Website:** [nhp.gov.in](https://www.nhp.gov.in)

